    "objectID": "sources.html",
    "href": "sources.html",
    "title": "Sources",
    "section": "",
    "text": "The data for this project comes from the U.S. Census Bureau’s American Community Survey (ACS) 5-year estimates, accessed through the tidycensus R package.\nVariables used:\n\nB15003_022: Number of individuals whose highest educational attainment is a bachelor’s degree\nB15003_001: Total population in the educational attainment table universe\n\nGeography:\n\ncensus tracts\nLos Angeles County, California\nACS 2022 5-year estimates\n\nProcessing steps:\n\nretrieve tract-level ACS data with geometry\nreshape the long ACS output into a wide tract-level table\ncompute bachelor’s degree attainment as a percentage of the total table population\nmap the results as a static choropleth and an interactive leaflet layer\n\nThis is a tract-level exploratory project intended to visualize educational inequality across neighborhoods."
  },
  {
    "objectID": "about.html",
    "href": "about.html",
    "title": "About",
    "section": "",
    "text": "I am Faran Abbas, a graduate student in World Economy at Shandong University. You can view my work on GitHub or contact me at faranabbas@hotmail.com.\nThis project maps bachelor’s degree attainment across Los Angeles County census tracts using American Community Survey data. It is designed as an education and regional-inequality portfolio project that connects spatial data analysis to human-capital and public-policy questions."
  },
